\n| last1 = Popper\n| first1 = Karl\n| journal = Dialectica\n| volume = 32\n| issue =3/4\n| pages =339\u2013355\n| title = Natural Selection and the Emergence of Mind\n| date = 1978\n| jstor = 42970324\n| doi=10.1111/j.1746-8361.1978.tb01321.x\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last1 = Popper\n| first1 = Karl\n| editor1-last = Bartley III\n| editor1-first=W.W.\n| title = Quantum Theory and the Schism in Physics: From the Postscript to the Logic of Scientific Discovery\n| date = 1982\n| orig-year = originally written in 1962\n| publisher = Routledge\n| isbn =  0415091128\n| edition=2005\n}}\n* {{Cite interview | ref = harv\n| last = Popper\n| first = Karl\n| interviewer = S. Lannes and A. Boyer\n| title = Les chemins de la verite: L'Express va plus loin avec Karl Popper\n| work = L'Express\n| date = 26 February 1982\n| year = 1982b\n| pages = 82-88\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last = Popper\n| first = Karl\n| title = Realism and the Aim of Science: From the Postscript to The Logic of Scientific Discovery\n| orig-year = originally written in 1962\n| date = 1983\n| publisher = Routledge\n| location = London and New York\n| isbn=0-415-08400-8\n| edition=1st\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| first = Karl\n| last = Popper\n| chapter = Zwei Bedeutungen von Falsifizierbarkeit [Two meanings of falsifiability]\n| language=german\n| editor1-first = H.\n| editor1-last = Seiffert\n| editor2-first = G.\n| editor2-last = Radnitzky \n| title = Handlexikon der Wissenschaftstheorie [Dictionary of epistemology]\n| publisher = Deutscher Taschenbuch Verlag \n| location = M\u00fcnchen \n| date = 1989\n| edition = 1992\n| isbn = 3-423-04586-8\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| first = Karl\n| last = Popper\n| year = 2009\n| orig-year = manuscript 1933, Published German 1979\n| editor-last = Eggers Hansen\n| editor-first = Troels\n| title = The Two Fundamental Problems of the Theory of Knowledge \n| publisher = Routledge \n| location = London and New York\n| translator-first = Andreas \n| translator-last = Pickel\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| title = Evolution\n| edition = 3rd\n| first = M\n| last = Ridley\n| publisher = Blackwell Publishing Limited\n| year = 2003\n| isbn = 1-4051-0345-0\n}}\n* {{Cite book| ref=harv\n| last = Rosende\n| first = Diego L.\n| chapter = Popper on Refutability : Some Philosophical and Historical Questions\n| title = Rethinking Popper\n| editor1-last = Parusnikova\n| editor1-first = Zuzana\n| editor2-last = Cohen\n| editor2-first = Robert S.\n| publisher = Springer\n| date = 2009\n| series = Boston Studies in the Philosophy of Science\n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last1 = Ruse\n| first1 = Michael\n| title = Science and Spirituality: Making Room for Faith in the Age of Science\n| date = 2010\n| publisher = Cambridge university press\n| location = New York\n| isbn = 978-0-521-75594-8\n| edition =1st\n}}\n* Sokal, Alan, and Bricmont, Jean, ''[[Fashionable Nonsense]]'', Picador, New York, NY, 1998.\n* {{cite journal | ref = harv\n| last = Soler\n| first = L\u00e9na\n| date = 2001\n| journal = Le Portique\n| series = \n| title = Certitudes, incertitudes et enjeux de la philosophie des sciences contemporaine\n| volume = 7\n| veditors =\n| pages =\n| url= http://journals.openedition.org:80/leportique/pdf/236\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171216013830/http://journals.openedition.org:80/leportique/pdf/236\n| archive-date = 2017-12-16\n}}\n* Theobald, D.L. (2006). [https://web.archive.org/web/20110514101850/http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/comdesc/default.html#evidence 29+ Evidences for Macroevolution: The Scientific Case for Common Descent.] ''The Talk.Origins Archive''. Version 2.87.\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last1 = Thornton \n| first1 = Stephen \n| editor1-last = Zalta \n| editor1-first = Edward N.\n| title = The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy\n| date = 2016\n| orig-year=original publication 1997\n| edition = Summer 2017\n| chapter = Karl Popper\n| chapter-url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2017/entries/popper/\n}}\n* {{Wikicite | ref = {{harvid|United States v. Prime|2002}}\n| reference={{cite court\n | litigants = United States v. Prime\n | court = W.D.Wash.\n | vol = 220\n | reporter = F. Supp. 2d\n | opinion=1203\n | url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170908102653/https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp2/220/1203/2533848/%7Cdate%3D2002%7D%7D%7C\n }}\n}}\n* {{cite magazine | ref = harv\n| last = Wallis\n| first = C\n| title = The Evolution Wars\n| magazine= Time Magazine\n| date = 2005-08-07\n| url = http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1090909,00.html\n| url-access = subscription \n<!-- | archive-url = http://cchadley.free.fr/2ndYr/2ndYrCiv/TDTexts2008-09/B2TDTimeEvolutionWarsAug2005.pdf--> \n}}\n* {{cite book | ref = harv\n| last = Watkins\n| first = John\n| title =  Criticism and the growth of knowledge\n| date = 1970\n| chapter = Against 'Normal Science'\n| pages = 25\u201337\n| editor1-first = Imre\n| editor1-last = Lakatos\n| editor2-first = Alan\n| editor2-last = Musgrave\n| publisher = Cambridge University Press\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Abbreviated references==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n{{philosophy of science}}\n{{Karl Popper}}\n{{Positivism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Analytic philosophy]]\n[[Category:Epistemology of science]]\n[[Category:Epistemological theories]]\n[[Category:Karl Popper]]\n[[Category:Razors (philosophy)]]\n", "name_user": "Dominic Mayers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBasic statements", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falsifiability"}
{"title_page": "Rona Munro", "text_new": "{{short description|Scottish writer}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Rona Munro\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1959|9|7}}\n| birth_place = [[Aberdeen]], Scotland\n| occupation = Writer\n}}\n\n'''Rona Munro''' (born 7 September 1959) is a Scottish writer. She has written plays for theatre, radio, and television. Her film work includes [[Ken Loach]]'s ''[[Ladybird, Ladybird (film)|Ladybird, Ladybird]]'' (1994), ''[[Oranges and Sunshine]]'' (2010) for [[Jim Loach]] and ''[[Aim\u00e9e & Jaguar]]'' (1999), co-authored by German director [[Max F\u00e4rberb\u00f6ck]].\n\n== Career ==\n\nRona Munro is known for being the author of the last ''[[Doctor Who]]'' television serial of the original run to air, ''[[Survival (Doctor Who)|Survival]]'' (1989). She later novelised this serial for [[Target Books]]. Munro returned to ''Doctor Who'' in 2016 to write the tenth episode of the tenth series, titled \"[[The Eaters of Light]]\", making her the only writer to date to have worked on the classic and revived eras of the show.<ref name=\"Munro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/series-10-classic-writer-returns-with-the-eaters-of-light-81668.htm |title=Series 10: Classic Writer Returns With \"The Eaters of Light\" |publisher=DoctorWhoTV |date=16 November 2016 |accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nHer history cycle The James Plays, ''James I'', ''James II'', and ''James III'', were first performed by the [[National Theatre of Scotland]] in summer 2014 in a co-production with [[Edinburgh International Festival]] and the National Theatre UK. Her other credits include the theatre play ''Iron'' which has received many productions worldwide. Other theatre works include plays for the [[Traverse Theatre]] Edinburgh (''Fugue'', ''Your Turn To Clean The Stair'', ''Strawberries in January'' translation), Manchester Royal Exchange (''Mary Barton'', ''Scuttlers''), Plymouth Drum Theatre and [[Paines Plough]] (''Long Time Dead''), and the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] (''The Indian Boy'', ''The Astronaut's Chair'').\n\nMunro has also contributed eleven dramas to [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]]'s ''Stanley Baxter Playhouse'': ''[[Marilyn Imrie#The Stanley Baxter Playhouse: First Impressions|First Impressions]]'', ''[[Marilyn Imrie#The Stanley Baxter Playhouse: Wheeling Them In|Wheeling Them In]]'', ''[[Marilyn Imrie#The Stanley Baxter Playhouse: The King's Kilt|The King's Kilt]]'', ''[[Marilyn Imrie#The Stanley Baxter Playhouse: Pasta Alfreddo at Cafe Alessandro|Pasta Alfreddo at Cafe Alessandro]]'', ''[[Marilyn Imrie#The Stanley Baxter Playhouse: The Man in the Garden|The Man in the Garden]]'', ''[[Marilyn Imrie#The Stanley Baxter Playhouse: The Porter's Story|The Porter's Story]]'', ''[[Marilyn Imrie#The Stanley Baxter Playhouse: The German Pilot|The German Pilot]]'', ''[[Marilyn Imrie#The Stanley Baxter Playhouse: The Spider|The Spider]]'', ''[[Marilyn Imrie#The Stanley Baxter Playhouse: The Showman|The Showman]]'', ''[[Marilyn Imrie#The Stanley Baxter Playhouse: Meg's Tale|Meg's Tale]]'', and ''[[Marilyn Imrie#The Stanley Baxter Playhouse: The Flying Scotsman|The Flying Scotsman]]''.\n\nIn 2006 the [[Lyric Theatre (Hammersmith)|Lyric Theatre, Hammersmith]] presented Munro's adaptation of [[Richard Adams]]' classic book ''[[Watership Down]]''. Her early television work includes episodes of the drama series ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' ([[BBC]]) and, more recently, a BBC film, ''Rehab'', directed by Antonia Bird.\n\nRona Munro currently lives and works in Scotland. Her play ''The Last Witch'' was performed at the 2009 [[Edinburgh Festival]], directed by [[Dominic Hill]], and in 2011 by [[Dumbarton People's Theatre]]. In 2018, a production of her adaptation of ''[[My Name Is Lucy Barton]]'' starring [[Laura Linney]] opened in London.\n\n==Awards==\n* [[Giles Cooper Award]] for ''Dirt Under The Carpet'', 1988\n* [[Susan Smith Blackburn Prize]], 1991\n* [[Evening Standard Award]], NOOK Award for Best Play for ''The James Plays'', 2014\n* [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain]] Award, Best Play for ''The James Plays'', 2014\n\n==Works==\n* ''The Bang and the Whimper'', 1982\n* ''The Salesman'', 1982\n* ''Fugue'', 1983\n* ''Bus'', 1984\n* ''Touchwood'', 1984\n* ''Ghost Story'', 1985\n* ''Piper's Cave'', 1985\n* ''Watching Waiters'', 1985\n* ''Biggest Party in the World'', 1986\n* ''Dust And Dreams'', 1986\n* ''The Way To Go Home'', 1987\n* ''Winners'', 1987\n* ''Off The Road'', 1988\n* ''[[Doctor Who]]'', \"[[Survival (Doctor Who)|Survival]]\", 1989\n* ''Long Story Short'', 1989\n* ''Saturday at the Commodore'', 1989\n* ''Bold Girls'', 1990<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.arts.gla.ac.uk/scotlit/asls/Laverock-Bold_Girls.html | work=The Association for Scottish Literary Studies | title=Making Them Bold And Breaking The Mould: Rona Munro\u2019s Bold Girls | year=1991 | author=Douglas Gifford | access-date=23 May 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090513043312/http://www.arts.gla.ac.uk/scotlit/asls/Laverock-Bold_Girls.html | archive-date=13 May 2009 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* ''Scotland Matters'', 1992\n* ''Your Turn To Clean The Stair'', 1992\n* ''Haunted'', 1999\n* {{cite book| title=The House of Bernarda Alba| year=1999| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-wxfoF4i3HMC&pg=PA1&lpg=PA1&dq=Rona+Munro| author=Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca| publisher=Nick Hern Books| isbn=978-1-85459-459-4|trans-title=Rona Munro }}\n* ''Snake'', 1999\n* {{cite book| title=Iron| year=2002| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uFWxWnq3k2QC&dq=Rona+Munro&printsec=frontcover| publisher=Nick Hern Books| isbn=978-1-85459-703-8}}\n* ''Stick Granny on the Roofrack'', 2002\n* ''Gilt'', 2003\n* ''Catch A Falling Star!'', 2004\n* ''Women on the Verge of a T Junction'', 2004\n* ''Indian Boy'', 2006\n* ''Long Time Dead'', 2006\n* ''The Maiden Stone'', 2006\n* ''Mary Barton'', 2006\n* ''Strawberries in January'', (translation) 2006\n* ''Watership Down'', 2006\n* ''Dirt Under The Carpet'', 2007\n*''[[The Last Witch]]'', 2009<ref name=higgins>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2009/aug/09/rona-munro-edinburgh-festival|title=Rona Munro burns bright at Edinburgh|first=Charlotte |last=Higgins|work=The Guardian|date=9 August 2009|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref>\n* ''Little Eagles'', 2011\n*''The Astronaut's Chair'', 2012\n* ''Donny's Brain'', 2012\n* ''The James Plays'', 2014\n* ''[[Scuttlers (play)|Scuttlers]]'', 2015\n* ''Doctor Who'', \"[[The Eaters of Light]]\", 2017\n* ''[[Rebus: Long Shadows]]'', 2018''<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/apr/09/inspector-rebus-scottish-detective-stage-debut-ian-rankin| title=Rebus: Rankin's gritty Scottish detective to make stage debut| publisher=[[The Guardian]] | work=theguardian.com | date=9 April 2018 | accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref>''\n*''[[My Name Is Lucy Barton]]'', 2018\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.personal.leeds.ac.uk/~ecl6nb/OnTarget/authors/munr/munro.htm Biography of Rona Munro at On Target]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060101165637/http://www.writewords.org.uk/interviews/rona_munro.asp Interview]\n*[http://www.doollee.com/PlaywrightsM/munro-rona.html ''Rona Munro'', doollee]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2009/aug/09/rona-munro-edinburgh-festival''Guardian'' interview preceding Edinburgh festival 2009.]\n\n{{John Whiting Award}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munro, Rona}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Writers from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Scottish dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Scottish television writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:British women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Women television writers]]\n